873	\section{Mayer-Vietoris LES sequence (iter-022)}
874	
875	After Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_delta} the third Mayer-Vietoris LES building block --- the connecting homomorphism $\delta$ --- is in scope. Combined with the iter-017 building blocks $\toBiprod$ (sum of two restriction maps) and $\fromBiprod$ (difference of two restriction maps), all three pieces of the LES are available. Iter-022 packages them into the standard $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}$-form sequence, mirroring Mathlib \texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/MayerVietoris.lean} L120--122.
876	
877	\begin{definition}[Mayer-Vietoris LES sequence (iter-022)]
878	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence}
879	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_sequence}
880	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_fromBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_delta}
881	  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a category equipped with a Grothendieck topology $J$ on which $\HasWeakSheafify\,J\,(\Type\,u)$, $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, and $\HasExt\,(\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$ all hold. Let $S : J.\MayerVietorisSquare$, $F : \Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)$, and $n_0, n_1 \in \mathbb N$ with $n_0 + 1 = n_1$. The \emph{Mayer-Vietoris long exact sequence} of $F$ at the square $S$ and adjacent degrees $(n_0, n_1)$ is the $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}$-form sequence
882	  \[
883	    \HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence}\,k\,S\,F\,n_0\,n_1\,h \;:=\; \mathtt{ComposableArrows.mk_5}\,(\toBiprod\,n_0)\,(\fromBiprod\,n_0)\,(\delta\,n_0\,n_1\,h)\,(\toBiprod\,n_1)\,(\fromBiprod\,n_1)
884	  \]
885	  in $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}\,\AddCommGrpCat\,5$, where the abbreviated arguments are $\toBiprod\,n := \HModulePrime\_\toBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n$, $\fromBiprod\,n := \HModulePrime\_\fromBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n$, and $\delta\,n_0\,n_1\,h := \HModulePrime\_\delta\,k\,S\,F\,n_0\,n_1\,h$.
886	\end{definition}
887	
888	\begin{proof}
889	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_fromBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_delta}
890	  Direct mirror of Mathlib's $\mathtt{GrothendieckTopology.MayerVietorisSquare.sequence}$ (\texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L120--122) with $F.\cohomologyPresheaf \rightarrow \HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F$ and the iter-021 $\delta$ in place of Mathlib's $S.\delta\,F$. The body is a one-line application of $\mathtt{ComposableArrows.mk_5}$ (\texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/ComposableArrows.lean}) which assembles five composable morphisms $f_0 : X_0 \to X_1$, $f_1 : X_1 \to X_2$, \ldots, $f_4 : X_4 \to X_5$ into a $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}\,C\,5$ object. Body:
891	  \begin{lstlisting}
892	  ComposableArrows.mk₅ (HModule'_toBiprod k S F n₀) (HModule'_fromBiprod k S F n₀)
893	    (HModule'_δ k S F n₀ n₁ h)
894	    (HModule'_toBiprod k S F n₁) (HModule'_fromBiprod k S F n₁)
895	  \end{lstlisting}
896	  The codomain $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}\,\AddCommGrpCat\,5$ inherits the $\AddCommGrpCat$-flavor from each individual building block (each lands in $\AddCommGrpCat$-morphisms because the iter-016 $\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n$ always lands in $C^{op} \to \AddCommGrpCat$, regardless of the value-category $\ModuleCat\,k$ of $F$ itself).
897	
898	  Declared as $\mathtt{noncomputable\ abbrev}$ (matches Mathlib L120). The $\mathtt{abbrev}$ form is required so that downstream code in iter-023+ $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequenceIso}$ and iter-024+ $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence\_exact}$ can unfold the body via $\mathtt{dsimp}$ to access $\mathtt{mk_5}$'s field-projection simp lemmas, which require unfoldability of the carrier. Plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe (iter-022) confirms the body typechecks end-to-end, kernel-only axioms.
899	\end{proof}
900	
901	\begin{remark}[Why iter-022 scope is just the sequence, not sequence+iso+exactness]
902	  Mathlib's MV-LES build-out continues from $\delta$ as: sequence (L120--122) $\to$ sequence-iso to $\Ext.\mathtt{contravariantSequence}$ (L124--138) $\to$ exactness theorem (L140--141) $\to$ $\delta$-zero $\mathtt{simp}$ companions (L143--149). The sequence-iso L124--138 is the technical heart: it requires four substantial auxiliary lemmas (Mathlib L48--106) involving $\Ext.\mathtt{biprodAddEquiv}$ and the $\AddCommGrpCat$-side biproduct-vs-product $\mathtt{addEquiv}$, all of which transfer to the $\ModuleCat\,k$ flavor but require careful handling of the per-fiber $\AddCommGrpCat$-vs-$\ModuleCat\,k$ distinction. Iter-022 lays only the sequence (the smallest useful unit downstream of iter-021); iter-023 will scaffold the four auxiliary lemmas + the sequence-iso (the substantive multi-iteration work); iter-024 will scaffold the exactness theorem + the $\mathtt{simp}$ companions.
903	
904	  Iter-022 sorry-count trajectory: $9 \to 10 \to 9$ (one new \lstinline{sorry} site in the $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence}$ abbrev; filled in the iter-022 prover round).
905	\end{remark}
906	
907	\section{Use in the project}
908	
909	The composition of the four typeclass instances of Sections~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}–\ref{sec:moduleK_ext}, Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}, and Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule} delivers Phase~A step~5 in full and bridges to Phase~A step~6:
910	
911	\begin{itemize}
912	  \item For $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$, the $\ModuleCat\,k$-flavoured cohomology
913	    \[
914	      H^n_{\Module\,k}(C, \struct C) \;:=\; \mathtt{HModule}\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,n
915	    \]
916	    is well-defined and automatically carries a $\Module\,k$ instance, so $\Module.\mathtt{finrank}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1) : \mathbb N$ is well-defined.
917	  \item The forgetful functor $\ModuleCat\,k \to \AddCommGrpCat$ recovers the iter-004 abelian-group cohomology (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf_forgetCompare}), so the new $\HModule$ commutes with the existing $\Sheaf.\mathtt H$ on the underlying type level.
918	  \item Phase~A step~6 (Serre finiteness, $\finrank_k H^i(C, \mathcal F) < \infty$) remains the deep work to come, but is now expressible inside Mathlib's standard $\Module\,k$ API: the statement of Serre finiteness becomes a $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,F\,n)$ predicate.
919	\end{itemize}

